{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569632"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22278"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22278"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.21,0.01,0.71,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15243"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108084"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15243"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90494"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108084"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a health check. She was diagnosed with stage 3b chronic kidney disease secondary to diabetic nephropathy two years ago. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and dyslipidaemia. Her medications include metformin, gliclazide, perindopril, amlodipine, and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Most recent blood tests show an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 32 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u003E90), potassium 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0), and sodium 144 mmol/L (135-145).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe mentions that she has been trying to reduce her salt intake by using a salt substitute she purchased from the supermarket.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate dietary advice regarding salt intake?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Use sea salt instead of table salt to reduce sodium intake","Salt intake should be reduced to \u003C10 g per day","Increase dietary salt intake to prevent hyponatraemia","Avoid salt substitutes as they often contain potassium chloride","Continue using salt substitutes as they are beneficial for blood pressure control"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has stage 3b chronic kidney disease (CKD) with a mildly elevated serum potassium level. The dietary advice should focus on both sodium restriction and avoiding further increases in potassium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid salt substitutes as they often contain potassium chloride\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate advice. Current guidelines recommend that people with CKD at risk of hyperkalaemia should avoid salt substitutes and use caution with reduced salt products that may contain potassium chloride. Patients with CKD (especially those with a reduced glomerular filtration rate) have a reduced ability to excrete potassium. This patient already has a mildly elevated potassium of 5.2 mmol/L - using a salt substitute could further increase her potassium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue using salt substitutes as they are beneficial for blood pressure control\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While reducing sodium intake is beneficial for blood pressure control, salt substitutes are not appropriate for this patient due to the risk of hyperkalaemia. Alternative methods of reducing sodium intake that don\u0027t involve potassium-based substitutes should be recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalt intake should be reduced to \u003C10 g per day\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Current guidelines recommend reducing salt intake to \u003C5 g per day for patients with CKD to help control blood pressure and reduce cardiovascular risk. A target of \u003C10 g per day is insufficient for optimal management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease dietary salt intake to prevent hyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This patient has normal sodium levels, and increasing salt intake would be contrary to recommendations for CKD management. Current guidelines recommend reducing salt intake to \u003C5 g/day for patients with CKD to help control blood pressure and reduce cardiovascular risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse sea salt instead of table salt to reduce sodium intake\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Sea salt and table salt contain similar amounts of sodium chloride. Using sea salt instead of table salt would not significantly reduce sodium intake. The focus should be on overall reduction of salt intake rather than substituting one form of salt for another.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this patient should include education about hidden sources of sodium and potassium in the diet, dietary advice to reduce sodium intake without using potassium-based substitutes, and regular monitoring of electrolyte levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Salt substitutes often contain potassium chloride and should be avoided in patients with chronic kidney disease due to risk of hyperkalaemia.","Dietary sodium restriction to less than 5 g per day is recommended for patients with chronic kidney disease.","Patients with chronic kidney disease should be educated about hidden sources of potassium in their diet, including certain reduced-salt products."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90494"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22278"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90494"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T14:26:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T14:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15243"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108084"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"de